First, we will perform PCA analysis on the data by treating each country’s food consumption as their “feature” vectors. In other words, we will find weight vectors to combine 20 food-item consumptions for each country.

def plot_weights(w_k):
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,12))
    
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(221)
    ax1.stem(w_k.T[0], basefmt='r', 
             use_line_collection=True)

    plt.xticks(range(len(w_k.T[1])), np.arange(1,len(w_k.T[1])+1))
    
    sns.despine()
        
    ax2.set_title("Weight Vector $w_2$")
        
def plot_items(Z, labels, size, grps=None):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=size)
    sc = sns.scatterplot(x=Z["PC1"], y=Z["PC2"],
                         hue=grps, s=120)

    sns.despine(offset=20)
    
    y_offset = np.ptp(Z["PC2"]) * 0.025
    x_offset = np.ptp(Z["PC1"]) * 0.02

    for i in range(len(labels)):
        sc.text(Z["PC1"][i]+x_offset, Z["PC2"][i]-y_offset, 
                labels[i], horizontalalignment="right",
                verticalalignment='center_baseline',
                size=13, color='DimGray')

def getPCA(X, K=2, norm=False):
    
    m, n = X.shape
    
    mu = np.mean(X, axis=0)
    
    if norm is True:
        # normalise data
        X_norm = (X-mu)/np.std(X, axis=0)
        
    else:
        X_norm = X-mu
        
    C = (X_norm.T @ X_norm)/m

    # eigenvalue decomposition
    lmbda, w = linalg.eig(C)
    
    # sort eigenvalues in descending order
    indices = lmbda.argsort()[::-1]
    lmbda = lmbda[indices]
    w = w[:, indices]

    # find K eigenvectors with largest eigenvalues
    w_k = w[:, 0:K]
    lmbda_k = lmbda[0:K]

    # get reduced representation
    Z = X_norm @ w_k
    Z = Z/np.sqrt(lmbda_k)

    return np.real(w_k), np.real(lmbda_k), np.real(Z)

def split_areas(x):
    area_list = []
    
    area_dict = {'Northern Europe': ['Denmark','Finland',
                                     'Norway','Sweden'],
                 'Western Europe': ['Austria','Belgium',
                                    'France','Germany',
                                    'Ireland','Luxembourg',
                                    'Holland','Switzerland',
                                    'England'],
                 'Southern Europe': ['Italy','Portugal',
                                     'Spain']}
    
    for k in area_dict:
        if x.name in area_dict[k]:
            return k

PCA separates the countries into the correct areas of Europe quite distinctly.

The Southern European countries have high positive loadings on PC1. As mentioned earlier, high consumption of garlic and olive oil contributes to most of the variance in PC1. We can thus reasonably conclude that people in Southern Europe consume a lot of garlic and olive oil.

The Northern European countries have moderate to high negative loadings on PC1 and PC2. This seems to indicate that people in Northern Europe don't consume much garlic and olive oil. Looking at the stem plots for $w_1$ and $w_2$, it seems that they consume a lot of crisp bread and moderate amounts of tinned soup, tinned fruit and jam.

With the exception of Austria, the Western European countries have moderate to high positive loadings on PC2. Except for Luxembourg, France, Belgium, Switzerland and Austria, they also have negative loadings on PC1. This seems to indicate that diets in Western Europe are varied, with those closer to Southern Europe having diets more similar to Southern European countries (i.e. more consumption of garlic and olive oil) and those closer to Northern Europe having diets more similar to Northern European countries (i.e. little consumption of garlic and olive oil). The obvious point of difference between Northern and Western Europe is the loading on PC2. The largest positive value of $w_2$ corresponds to consumption of instant coffee. This seems to indicate that Western European countries with high positive loadings (i.e. England and Luxembourg) consume a lot of instant coffee.

Order of faces using ISOMAP¶


This question aims to reproduce the ISOMAP algorithm results in the original paper for ISOMAP, J.B. Tenenbaum, V. de Silva, and J.C. Langford, Science 290 (2000) 2319-2323 that we have also seen in the lecture as an exercise.

The file isomap.mat (or isomap.dat) contains 698 images, corresponding to different poses of the same face. Each image is given as a 64 × 64 luminosity map, hence represented as a vector in $\mathbb{R}^{4096}$. This vector is stored as a row in the file.

In this question, you are expected to implement the ISOMAP algorithm by coding it up yourself. Choose the Euclidean distance (i.e., in this case, a distance in $\mathbb{R}^{4096}$) to construct the nearest neighbor graph—vertices corresponding to the images. Construct a similarity graph with vertices corresponding to the images, and tune the threshold $\epsilon$ so that each node has at least 100 neighbors (this approach corresponds to the so-called $\epsilon$-Isomap).

def getKNN(A, nn):
    
    N, M = A.shape
    
    W = np.zeros((N, N))

    for i in range(N):
        r_ix = np.setdiff1d(np.argsort(A[i]), [i], 
                            assume_unique=True)
        r_ix = r_ix[:nn]
        W[i, r_ix] = A[i, r_ix]

    return W

def getEpsNN(A, nn, eps):
    
    N, M = A.shape
    
    W = np.zeros((N, N))
    
    for i in range(N):
        poss_nn = (A[i] <= A[i].mean()*eps).nonzero()
        nn_ix = np.setdiff1d(poss_nn, [i], assume_unique=True)
        
        # increase eps until number of possible neighbours = nn
        if nn_ix.shape[0] < nn:
            return getEpsNN(A, nn, eps+0.0005)
        
        W[i, nn_ix] = A[i, nn_ix]
       
    return W

def getIsomap(A, nn=100, K=2, method='epsNN'):
    
    N, M = A.shape
    
    if method is 'epsNN':
        # get weighted graph using epsilon threshold method
        W = getEpsNN(A, nn, 0.8)
    else:
        W = getKNN(A, nn)
    
    # get shortest distances
    D = dijkstra(W, directed=False)
    
    I = np.identity(N)
    ones = np.ones(N)
    H = I - ((1/N)*ones.T*ones)

    C = -0.5*(H @ (D**2) @ H)
    
    # eigenvalue decomposition
    lmbda, w = linalg.eigh(C)

    indices = lmbda.argsort()[::-1]
    lmbda = lmbda[indices]
    w = w[:, indices]
    
    # find K eigenvectors with largest eigenvalues
    w_k = w[:, 0:K]
    lmbda_k = lmbda[0:K]
    
    # get reduced representation
    Z = (np.sqrt(np.diag(lmbda_k)) @ w_k.T).T
    
    return w_k, lmbda_k, Z

def plotImages(isomap_df, im_df):
    
    x_size = (max(isomap_df['PC1']) - min(isomap_df['PC1'])) * 0.05
    y_size = (max(isomap_df['PC2']) - min(isomap_df['PC2'])) * 0.05

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14,12))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)

    for i in np.linspace(300, 600, 30, dtype='int64'):
        
        x0 = isomap_df.loc[i, 'PC1'] - (x_size/2)
        y0 = isomap_df.loc[i, 'PC2'] - (y_size/2)
        x1 = isomap_df.loc[i, 'PC1'] + (x_size/2)
        y1 = isomap_df.loc[i, 'PC2'] + (y_size/2)

        img = im_df.iloc[i, :].values.reshape(64,64)
        ax.imshow(img, aspect='auto', cmap=plt.cm.gray, 
                interpolation='nearest', zorder=100000, 
                extent=(x0, x1, y0, y1))

    sns.scatterplot(x=isomap_df['PC1'], y=isomap_df['PC2'], alpha=0.7)

    sns.despine()

While PCA does show some picture clusters that have a visible element of similarity (e.g. the cluster at the bottom of the plot shows pictures angled down and/or facing right), these appear to be based more on the amount of light and shadow in the images. The images with faces with deep shadows are clustered at the top left corner of the plot and those with less shadow and brighter lighting are clustered at the bottom or the far right of the plot. PCA does not separate the images into categories more meaningful than the degree of light and shadow.

The ISOMAP projection is much clearer and more meaningful, because we can clearly see the images separated into distinct groups depending on the direction the face is looking and whether it is angled up or down.
